''' ({{zh|s={{linktext|\u5b89\u5e86}} |t=\u5b89\u6176 |p=\u0100nq\u00ecng |l=Peaceful Celebration}}, also Anking, formerly '''Hwaining''', now the name of [[Huaining County]]) is a [[prefecture-level city]] in the southwest of [[Anhui]] [[province of China|province]], People's Republic of China. Its population was 5,311,579 at the 2010 census, with 780,514 living in the built-up (''or metro'') area.\n\n==History==\nAnqing was held by the [[Taiping Heavenly Kingdom]] for almost nine years, from June 1853 to December 1861. It served as the capital of the Taiping's Anhui province during this period.<ref>\nThe Taiping Heavenly Kingdom: Rebellion and the Blasphemy of Empire. By Thomas H. Reilly</ref> The final [[Battle of Anqing]] and Qing attempt to retake the city began in 1860, and the [[Xiang Army]] and other Qing forces were able to retake the city by December 1861.\n\n==Culture==\nThe people of Anqing have a unique dialect that belongs to the [[Gan Chinese]] branch and is therefore quite different from the rest of the province, which is predominantly [[Huizhou Chinese]] speaking.<ref>Yan, Margaret Mian (2006). Introduction to Chinese Dialectology. LINCOM Europa. p. 148. {{ISBN|978-3-89586-629-6}}.</ref><ref>Kurpaska, Maria (2010). Chinese Language(s): A Look Through the Prism of \"The Great Dictionary of Modern Chinese Dialects\". Walter de Gruyter. p. 70. {{ISBN|978-3-11-021914-2}}.</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nThe [[prefecture-level city]] of Anqing administers 10 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|county-level divisions]], including 3 [[District of China|districts]], 2 [[county-level city|county-level cities]] and 5 [[County (People's Republic of China)|counties]]\u3002\n*[[District of China|District]]\n**[[Yingjiang District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8fce\u6c5f\u533a}})\n**[[Daguan District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5927\u89c2\u533a}})\n**[[Yixiu District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b9c\u79c0\u533a}})\n*[[County-level city]]\n**[[Tongcheng, Anhui|Tongcheng]] ({{lang|zh|\u6850\u57ce\u5e02}})\n**[[Qianshan, Anhui|Qianshan]] ({{lang|zh|\u6f5c\u5c71\u5e02}})\n*[[County (People's Republic of China)|County]]\n**[[Huaining County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6000\u5b81\u53bf}})\n**[[Taihu County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u592a\u6e56\u53bf}})\n**[[Susong County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5bbf\u677e\u53bf}})\n**[[Wangjiang County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u671b\u6c5f\u53bf}})\n**[[Yuexi County, Anhui|Yuexi County]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5cb3\u897f\u53bf}})\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Map\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Anqing.png|width=584|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=1750|y=1070|scale=584/1980|text=[[Yingjiang District|'''Yingjiang''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1500|y=1130|scale=584/1980|text=[[Daguan District|'''Daguan''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1650|y=940|scale=584/1980|text=[[Yixiu District|'''Yixiu''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1260|y=1030|scale=584/1980|text=[[Huaining County|'''Huaining<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=540|y=1140|scale=584/1980|text=[[Taihu County|'''Taihu<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=610|y=1730|scale=584/1980|text=[[Susong County|'''Susong<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1170|y=1550|scale=584/1980|text=[[Wangjiang County|'''Wangjiang<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=550|y=570|scale=584/1980|text=[[Yuexi County, Anhui|'''Yuexi<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1400|y=440|scale=584/1980|text=[[Tongcheng, Anhui|'''Tongcheng<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=990|y=780|scale=584/1980|text=[[Qianshan, Anhui|'''Qianshan<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n|}\n\n==Geography==\n<!--\n{{climate chart\n| Anqing\n| 1.3| 7.4| 48\n| 3.0| 9.3| 71\n| 7.0|13.7|133\n|13.1|20.7|164\n|18.4|25.8|192\n|22.3|29.0|280\n|25.7|32.5|196\n|25.3|32.2|130\n|20.7|27.5| 88\n|15.1|22.3| 82\n| 8.7|16.2| 57\n| 3.3|10.4| 33\n|float = right\n|clear = none}}\n-->\n\nAnqing is located in the southwestern part of Anhui province, and on the northern shore of the lower Yangtze. To the north are the [[Dabie Mountains]]. Neighbouring prefectures are:\n\n*[[Tongling]] (E)\n*[[Chizhou]] (SE)\n*[[Jiujiang]], [[Jiangxi]] (S)\n*[[Huanggang, Hubei|Huanggang]], [[Hubei]] (W)\n*[[Lu'an]] (N)\n*[[Hefei]] (NE)\n\nThe total area of the prefecture is {{convert|16300|km2|sigfig=3}}, with an urban area of {{convert|550|km2|sigfig=3}}, which is only 3.4% of the total.\n\n===Climate===\nAnqing has a four-season, [[monsoon]]-influenced [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Cfa''), with chilly, damp winters and very hot, humid summers. Cold northwesterly winds from Siberia can occasionally cause nightly temperatures to drop below freezing (although snow is uncommon), while summer can see extended periods of {{convert|35|\u00b0C}}+ days. The monthly 24-hour average temperature ranges from {{convert|4.3|\u00b0C|1}} in January to {{convert|29.2|\u00b0C|1}} in July, while the annual mean is {{convert|17.20|\u00b0C|1}}. Precipitation tends to reach a maximum in tandem with the ''[[meiyu]]'' (plum rains) while wintertime rainfall is generally light. With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 30% in March to 54% in August, the city receives 1,831 hours of bright sunshine annually.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Anqing (1981\u22122010)\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 22.8\n|Feb record high C = 27.4\n|Mar record high C = 32.1\n|Apr record high C = 33.8\n|May record high C = 35.8\n|Jun record high C = 38.3\n|Jul record high C = 39.5\n|Aug record high C = 40.9\n|Sep record high C = 38.0\n|Oct record high C = 34.3\n|Nov record high C = 29.7\n|Dec record high C = 24.5\n|Jan high C =  7.6\n|Feb high C = 10.0\n|Mar high C = 14.6\n|Apr high C = 21.2\n|May high C = 26.6\n|Jun high C = 29.4\n|Jul high C = 32.9\n|Aug high C = 32.2\n|Sep high C = 28.0\n|Oct high C = 22.7\n|Nov high C = 16.5\n|Dec high C = 10.4\n|year high C = 21.0\n|Jan mean C =  4.3\n|Feb mean C =  6.6\n|Mar mean C = 10.7\n|A